<Author>diva80
<Content>Comfortable, modern and funky! My husband and I stayed at the ME Melia for 3 nights last week and enjoyed our stay. To minimise on cost, we took a Deluxe room (which despite the posh sounding name is a standard room!). It was very small, but as we weren't planning on spending that much time in the room and it was a short stay, we didn't mind. If we had been there for a week then we definitely would have chosen a larger Supreme room. Our room was clean, cosy and comfortable though.All we could see from our window was a white wall outside, but we weren't too fussed about that. The DVD player was a very nice touch, as TV channels in hotels can often be quite limiting. When you come back in the evening, there is a nice lips-shaped chocolate on your bed, along with a small candle by the bedside.The bathroom was lovely, and the shower is amazing!! They provide lovely Aveda products and good quality robe and towels. There is plenty of storage space too.I took my own teabags but unfortunately there was not a kettle in the room, I am not sure if the larger rooms would have had one. Although we didn't ask them much, the staff we encountered were friendly and helpful. This is definitely a hotel for the younger crowd as the staff are all young and hip, and often wearing designer clothing.The location of the hotel is excellent, Plaza de Santa Ana is where there are a lot of cafes and bars for the evening, and it is within walking distance of the main shopping area (Sol/Gran Via). We even walked to the museums, although it took about 20-30 mins, but we wanted the exercise.We popped up to the rooftop bar to have a look, and it looked really nice but was closed when we went (monday evening) but on a weekend it is supposed to be excellent. The whole hotel has a nice modern funky feel to it.Although this is a hotel review, I will say a few other things about my trip in general!If you have a sweet tooth, you must have some chocolate y churros (long donuts with very thick hot chocolate) from Chocolateria San Gines, they are to die for! we had it about 5 times in 3 days, so you can imagine how much we loved them! Also just opposite it is a nice italian place with excellent quality pizza, but I forget the name. We also went to a chain called Ginos but the pizza there was awful! A friend recommended Siam which is a Thai restaurant on Calle San Bernadino near Plaza de Espana which was really nice, and although was hidden away, seemed to be popular and full of people. Somehow I didn't manage to find a good place for tapas, but am sure there are plenty of places, probably in side streets. All in all I thoroughly enjoyed my trip, and would definitely consider staying at the ME again. 
