<Author>seanyj
<Content>Fantastic...but, not perfect. The hotel is in a fantastic location. Extremely central to old Madrid and ideal to explore the city.Very contemporary and highly chic, the hotel has a very modern designer fell throughout and will not let you down if that's your bag.The room was very clean and the bed huge. The space around the bed was limited although the built-in 32 flat screen tv and lighting control panel made up for this. The bathroom was wonderful and although lacking a bath the powershower had hydro massage built-in and really does give a fantastic shower.On arrival the reception staff were friendly, warm and efficient. The man that dealt with us really was great as was the original concierege (Chemo) who was so friendly and nothing seemed to much for him.The paradox was that the front desk staff seemed to be largely highly efficient unlike some (not all!) of the staff in The Penthouse (rooftop bar). On the Sunday the bar was closed due to rain. We had got a bottle of wine and had one of the beds, which are canvas enclosed spaces shielding you from the elements and allowing you to enjoy the views from the bar. The staff said we had to vacate the bed and go inside because they needed to store things in the space. Ok, I understand that they need to protect the furnishings, but when we were asked to go inside there was no room at all to sit. We decided to go to our room with the wine and they said that this was fine but we couldn't take the ice bucket with us! This meant that we would to have had to get room service to bring a new bucket at a charge.The next day The Penthouse was meant to be closed and we found that it was in fact open. We decided to have a drink or two and found that the barman couldn't even muster a smile or even a hint of warmth despite attempting to engage him. This is sad as it lets down the other staff who seem to work so hard to give a genuine sense of warmth.The strange thing is that you are limited as to where you can sit on The Rooftop as alot of prime seating areas are cordoned off for bottle service only. This means that to sit in these areas you have to purchase a bottle off the menu. With the cheapest bottle at 150 euros and being spirits, it makes sitting anywhere truly nice unfeasible if there is just two of you and you don't want to die from alcohol poisoning. As residents it would be nice if they reviewed this and at quieter times open up the prime seating to at least residents. I do understand this policy at busy times but the bar was nearly empty!The final day was marred by a pushy maid who at 09:30 knocked our door to see if she could clean it! Check-out time is at 12:00! She then knocked again at 11:30 and someone else came in to check the mini-bar in between those times. I'm sure it's not the case, but the maid made us feel as if she wanted us out early so she could get her work out the way!Some lovely treats were left in the rooms from the aura experience management and the food in Midnight Rose is great.On Madrid, please don't bother going if you're a vegetarian (my partner is!) and if you like Tea, bring some with you! 
